name: Bouldering The Gorilla's Nest (aka No Fear No Sorrow)
author: Kyle O'Meara
embed: <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/134894423?title=0&byline=0&portrait=0&badge=0&autopause=0&player_id=0&app_id=137790" width="720" height="1280" frameborder="0" title="Bouldering The Gorilla's Nest (aka No Fear No Sorrow)" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>
description: Spectacular boulder problem in Gold Bar Washington with a crazy staired landing. Years ago, a tree fell in front of this giant block that enabled some motivated climbers to use the fallen tree as a foundation for a radical landing platform. From the ground, roughly 9 ft below the landing, you end up actually climbing up through a large hole in the stack of sticks and logs before getting over the platform where you climb up to a very airy and committing finish. One of the best I've ever climbed in those woods!!

name: Washington Climbing Conservation Initiative (WCCI)
author: Washington Climbers Coalition
embed: <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/238214936?title=0&byline=0&portrait=0&badge=0&autopause=0&player_id=0&app_id=137790" width="1920" height="1080" frameborder="0" title="Washington Climbing Conservation Initiative (WCCI)" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>
description:
In 2017, the Washington Climbers Coalition launched the Washington Climbing Conservation Initiative (WCCI) as a regional stewardship program to address the increasing impacts of growing climbing use at cherished climbing areas across the state. Together with Access Fund Conservation Team West and state land agencies, the initiative has executed 11 weeks of professional trail work at crags and bouldering areas across the state. As of the end of 2017, the initiative had engaged 290 volunteers in over 2,300 hours of work at four locations: Gold Bar, Exit 38 Farside, Index, and Tieton Canyon.

This initiative was made possible by a generous grant from REI with matching funds from WCC, the Seattle Bouldering Project, and individual donors.

Big thanks to the following supporting partners: Cascade Designs, Outdoor Research, Edgeworks, the Mountaineers, Mountains to Sound Greenway Trust, Stone Gardens, Vertical World, American Alpine Club, The North Face, Washington Alpine Club, DNR, WDFW, and State Parks.

Video by Ben Neilson  www.benneilsonmedia.com

name: Declaration of Elation
author: Aaron Englert
embed: <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/61493508?title=0&byline=0&portrait=0&badge=0&autopause=0&player_id=0&app_id=137790" width="1280" height="720" frameborder="0" title="Declaration of Elation" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>
description:
Obesity Direct is an overhung problem set on Fraggle Rock in the Clear Cut bouldering area of Gold Bar, Washington.  I have been working it on and off for a few year.  In truth it has been my nemeses.  This video catalogs some of those experiences.  
Thanks to all of you who made the hike up with me, those days have been some of best days out.  And a special shout out to Derek and Erin, good times.
